quran[6]{c,v,t,f}:
  2,225,"Allah does not hold you<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>accountable for idle talk involving your<i class=""s"">(unintended) </i>oaths, but He holds you accountable for what your hearts have earned, for Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Forbearing."
  2,226,"For those who vow abstinence from their wives is a wait of four months. But if they retract, then Allah is Oft-Forgiving, Bestowing of mercy."
  2,227,"But if they resolve to divorce—then Allah is indeed All-Hearing, All-Knowing."
  2,228,"Moreover, divorced women shall keep themselves in wait for three periods, and it is not lawful for them to conceal what Allah has created in their wombs if they believe in Allah and the Last Day, for their husbands have the right to restore them back if they want reconciliation. And women have rights equal to their obligations in accordance with what is fair. But men have a degree over them, for Allah is Almighty, All-Wise."
  2,229,"Divorce is<i class=""s"">(allowed) </i>twice, then either retention in accordance with what is fair, or setting free kindly. And it is not lawful for you<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>to take back anything you have given them{1}, unless <span class=",footnotes:1:“Them” is feminine, denoting that the discourse is addressing men regarding their wives.,footnotes:2:A grammatical shift from 2<sup><small>nd</small></sup> person to 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person.,footnotes:3:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…unless it is feared that they both may not maintain…”</span>,footnotes:4:Literally ‘ransoms herself’.
  2,230,"But if he divorces her, she shall not be lawful for him again until she has married another spouse. Then if he{1} divorces her, then no sin is committed by them both{2}if they reunite, provided they think they can maintain Allah’s limits. Thus these are Allah’s limits; He makes them evident to people who know.",footnotes:1:The latter.,footnotes:2:She and the first husband.
